Author: Sunopsis Version: 4.0 Last Update: DEC-2004
Description: - Loading Knowledge Module - Loads data from a File to a DB2 UDB database using the native CLP LOAD Command. - Depending on the file type (Fixed or Delimited) this KM will generate the appropriate LOAD script in a temporary directory. This script is then executed and automatically deleted at the end of the execution. - When an error occurs in the "Execute Load Command Script" step, it is recommanded to edit the log files created in the work directory defined in the physical schema of the source file. These files give additional explanation on the LOAD process.
Restrictions: - The source file must be accessible to the machine runing the Sunopsis Agent. - The DB2 script file (.db2) and the log files (.log) are placed in the work directory defined in the physical schema of the source file - The IBM DB2 Command Line Processor (CLP) as well as the IBM DB2 Connect Software must be installed on the machine running the Sunopsis Agent. - Make sure that the Data Server checkbox is checked in your Topology for the DB2 UDB Technology and, for your target DB2 UDB Database, specify the Database name in the Server field of the Data Server definition. To do that: 1. Edit the "IBM DB2 UDB" Technology definition in the Topology 2. Check the Naming Rules -> Using "Data Server" checkbox 3. Used Term : "Server" 4. Apply your changes 5. Edit your target DB2 UDB Dataserver definiton 6. In the Server field, enter the DB2 UDB Database name - The user specified in the IBM DB2 Data Server in the Sunopsis Topology must have enough privileges to run the LOAD utility (this can be achieved with a GRANT LOAD ON DATABASE statement). - As this KM uses the metadata of the source file, all the mappings containing file columns must be executed on the Staging Area. - This KM cannot be used with multiple record format files. - The default timestamp format is set to YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS. - Specify appropriate option values according to their description. - Journalizing Options are not implemented in this module.
Call command to execute a shell
Enter the name of the command shell specific processor. Examples: - On Windows: DB2CMD /c /w OR cmd.exe /c - On Unix / Linux: sh -c OR db2cmd -c -w
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.

Additionnal options used when creating the C$ temporary table. You can use this option if you want to create the temporary table in a nologging mode (transaction is not written in the DB2 log files) or if you want to specify a tablespace name. Examples: - Disable logging: NOT LOGGED INITIALLY - Specify a tablespace: IN MY_TABLESPACE NOT LOGGED INITIALLY - Compress Values: VALUE COMPRESSION
Timestamp Format in the source file
Specify the timestamp format in the file according to the DB2 LOAD utility documentation. Example: YYYY - Year MM - Month DD - Day etc.
